          "body": "The verb *didomi* (give) occurs seventeen times in this chapter, and a clear pattern emerges: the Father has *given* the Son a people. *Those whom You have given Me out of the world* (v. 6); *those whom You have given Me, for they are Yours* (v. 9); *those whom You have given Me* (vv. 11, 24). The elect are described as the Father's gift to the Son before they ever exercise faith. They were *Yours, and You gave them to Me* (v. 6). Reformed exegetes — Calvin, Owen, Carson in his *Pillar* volume — read this as the high-water mark of the Johannine doctrine of effectual calling: the church is the Father's love-gift to the Son, secured in eternity, manifested in time. Arminian readers (e.g., I. Howard Marshall) acknowledge the language but stress conditional reception; both orthodox traditions agree that the gift-language assigns initiative to the Father. The reader who has come to Christ has been *given* to Christ — that is the chapter's claim, not the reader's choice."
