          "body": "The third movement (vv. 20-26) widens to *those also who believe in Me through their word* — every believer reading the Gospel of John, including you. The dominant petition is *that they may be one*, repeated four times (vv. 11, 21, 22, 23). The benchmark is intra-Trinitarian: *as You, Father, are in Me and I in You, that they also may be in Us* (v. 21). This is not organizational uniformity but participatory communion — believers drawn into the very life of Father and Son. The unity has an evangelistic edge: *so that the world may believe that You sent Me* (v. 21) and *so that the world may know that You sent Me, and loved them, even as You have loved Me* (v. 23). Christian disunity is not merely embarrassing; it is theologically falsifying. The world is meant to read the Father's love for the Son in the church's love for one another."
